liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: What are the lasting effects of the Voice Referendum? Whether it gets up, or fails to pass, the fallout from this campaign will be felt long after. How is it playing out for Indigenous people now? And what impact will it have on our international reputation? In the final weeks before the Referendum, ABC's Carly Williams and Fran Kelly discuss what the outcome will mean for Australians beyond the vote. You can watch the video below.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Australian Electoral Commission (AEC) says Friday was the biggest single-day of pre-polling in Australia's history, with just over 1 million votes cast. In total, the AEC says early voting (postal and in-person) now adds up to about 8.41 million people. "Overall, around 6.13 million people voted at an early voting centre," the AEC says. "This compares to 5.6 million at the 2022 federal election making the referendum pre-poll period the largest number of votes cast at early voting centres in Australia's history." The AEC says there are 17.6 million people enrolled to vote, so around 9.2 million people will need to visit a polling place today. Of the 17.6 million people on the electoral roll, around 9.2 million need to visit a polling place today.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 8.41 million Australians have already voted

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Polling centres have opened for people in some eastern states to cast their vote in this year's Voice to Parliament Referendum — with millions expected to vote in person. Yes and No campaigners are handing out flyers and speaking with voters queuing up outside centres, however, campaigning is not allowed inside or within six metres of entrances. Out in Melbourne's north at the Northern School for Autism in Reservoir, voters are turning up in droves. The state is waiting to see which way Victoria will swing, with more than 50 per cent of Victorians expected to vote in person today. As the sun rises over Redfern, Sydneysiders line up early. Yes campaigner Franz has arrived early to a polling booth in Sydney. "It's going to be tough, but we just have to hope for the best," he says. Polls open at 8am in your local timezone.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: People across Australia line up early to cast their vote

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The first of several flights carrying Australians out of Israel has arrived safely in London after leaving Tel Aviv's Ben Gurion Airport on Friday afternoon local time. The flight contained 238 passengers. Qantas also has another flight planned for Sunday, and two charter flights have also been arranged. Speaking ahead of the flight's arrival, Australia's high commissioner to the UK, Stephen Smith, said: "It's always great, as an Australian official, to help people out of harm's way." The ABC's Mitch Woolnough was at the airport in Tel Aviv to cover the flight's departure, and took these snaps.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Australian repatriation flight lands safely in London

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: It's just gone past midnight in Israel, meaning the IDF's deadline for civilians to evacuate northern Gaza has passed. Médecins Sans Frontières (Doctors Without Borders) is reporting that the deadline issued to the Al Awda Hospital in Nuseirat refugee camp to evacuate by midnight alongside the rest of the population has been extended to 6am. "The evacuation of patients remains complicated," MSF said in a tweet. Meanwhile, CNN is reporting that US President Joe Biden gave a one-word answer when asked what worried him about a ground invasion of Gaza: "Death." The president was speaking with attendees after delivering a speech on the US economy in Philadelphia on Friday.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Midnight deadline passes, Biden fears civilian deaths

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Reuters is reporting that one of its news videographers, Issam Abdallah, was killed on Friday while working in southern Lebanon. The news agency says it is seeking more information and working with the authorities in the region. Earlier, Reuters reported that Israeli shelling had struck a Lebanese army observation post at the border. The Israeli military said it fired in response to a suspected armed infiltration, which it later said had been a false alarm. Israel's UN envoy, Gilad Erdan, said it would investigate what had happened in the area following the journalist's death. "We always try to mitigate and avoid civilian casualties. Obviously, we would never want to hit or kill or shoot any journalist that is doing its job," Mr Erdan said.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Reuters journalist killed in southern Lebanon
